div.p:
2. If Japan renounces sovereignty in favor of no one, this would create a chaotic international situation, particularly if, as is possible, the United Nations does not approve the trusteeship agreement we shall propose. It might then be claimed
a)
that sovereignty was vested in the inhabitants, who could hereafter assert, perhaps with United Nations backing, a right to oust the United States;
b)
that the victors in the war over Japan, including the U.S.S.R., have an inchoate right to sovereignty of these islands renounced by Japan in favor of no one in particular;
c)
that the United Nations is entitled to deal, in its own way, with the islands and their inhabitants;
d)
that the United States has, by a subterfuge, actually acquired the sovereignty.
